You can also retrieve a class object from a specific remote computer. Most class\nobjects implement the IClassFactory interface. You would then call CreateInstance to create an\nuninitialized object. It is not always necessary to go through this process however. To create a single\nobject, call the CoCreateInstanceEx function, which allows you to create an instance on a remote\nmachine. This replaces the CoCreateInstance function, which can still be used to create an instance\non a local computer. Both functions encapsulate connecting to the class object, creating the instance,\nand releasing the class object. Two other functions, CoGetInstanceFromFile and CoGetInstanceFromIStorage,\nprovide both instance creation on a remote system and object activation. There are numerous\nfunctions and interface methods whose purpose is to create objects of a single type and provide a\npointer to an interface on that object."

CreateProcessWithLogonW requires no special privileges,\nbut the specified user account must be allowed to log on interactively. Generally, it is best\nto use CreateProcessWithLogonW to create a process with alternate credentials."

  DllCallCredGetTargetInfo: "DllCall(\"Advapi32\\CredGetTargetInfo\", \"_In_ LPCTSTR\", TargetName,\"_In_ DWORD\", Flags,\"_Out_ PCREDENTIAL_TARGET_INFORMATION\", *TargetInfo, \"BOOL\")\nThe CredGetTargetInfo function retrieves all known target name information for the named target computer.\nThis executed locally and does not need any particular privilege. The information returned is\nexpected to be passed to the CredReadDomainCredentials and CredWriteDomainCredentials functions. The\ninformation should not be used for any other purpose.\nAuthentication packages compute TargetInfo when\nattempting to authenticate to a TargetName. The authentication packages cache this target information\nto make it available to CredGetTargetInfo. Therefore, the target information will only be available\nfrom a recent attempt to authenticate a TargetName.\nAuthentication packages not in the LSA process\ncan cache a TargetInfo for later retrieval by CredGetTargetInfo by calling CredReadDomainCredentials\nwith the CRED_CACHE_TARGET_INFORMATION flag."

  DllCallCredMarshalCredential: "DllCall(\"Advapi32\\CredMarshalCredential\", \"_In_ CRED_MARSHAL_TYPE\", CredType,\"_In_ PVOID\", Credential,\"_Out_ LPTSTR\", *MarshaledCredential, \"BOOL\")\nThe CredMarshalCredential function transforms a credential into a text string. Historically, many functions,\nsuch as NetUseAdd, take a domain name, user name, and password as credentials. These functions\ndo not accept certificates as credentials. The CredMarshalCredential function converts such credentials\ninto a form that can be passed into these APIs.\nThe marshaled credential should be passed as\nthe user name string to any API that is currently passed credentials. The domain name, if applicable,\npassed to that API should be passed as NULL or empty. For certificate credentials, the PIN of the\ncertificate should be passed to that API as the password.\nThe caller should not modify or print marshaled\ncredentials. The returned value can be freely converted between the Unicode, ANSI, and OEM characters\nsets. The string is case sensitive."

  DllCallCryptRegisterOIDInfo: "DllCall(\"Crypt32\\CryptRegisterOIDInfo\", \"_In_ PCCRYPT_OID_INFO\", pInfo,\"_In_ DWORD\", dwFlags, \"BOOL\")\nThe CryptRegisterOIDInfo function registers the OID information specified in the CRYPT_OID_INFO structure,\npersisting it to the registry.\nCrypt32.dll contains predefined information for the commonly known\nOIDs. This function allows applications to augment the predefined OID information. During CryptRegisterOIDInfo's\nfirst call, the registered OID information is installed.\nWhen expanding the tables\nusing CryptRegisterOIDInfo, the new entries can be placed either before or after predefined entries,\ncontrolled by dwFlags. The placement of registered OID information affects the result of CryptFindOIDInfo\nbecause the tables are searched in order. First registered entries placed before the predefined\nentries are checked, then the predefined entries are checked, and finally, registered entries placed\nafter the predefined entries are checked. The first match found is returned. A newly registered\nentry placed before the predefined entries can override one of the predefined entries."

  DllCallGdiplusNotificationHook: "DllCall(\"gdiplus\\GdiplusNotificationHook\", \"OUT ULONG_PTR\", *token, \"GpStatus\")\ncalled by wrapper methods.The GdiplusStartup function returns (in its output parameter) a pointer to\na GdiplusStartupOutput structure. One of the members of the structure is a pointer to a notification\nhook function that has the same signature as GdiplusNotificationHook. There are two ways you can call\nthe notification hook function; you can use the pointer returned by GdiplusStartup or you can call\nGdiplusNotificationHook. In fact, GdiplusNotificationHook simply verifies that you have suppressed\nthe background thread and then calls the notification hook function that is returned by GdiplusStartup.\nThe token parameter receives an identifier that you should later pass in a corresponding call\nto the notification unhook function."
  DllCallGdiplusNotificationUnhook: "DllCall(\"gdiplus\\GdiplusNotificationUnhook\", \"ULONG_PTR\", token, \"VOID\")\ncalled by wrapper methods.The GdiplusStartup function returns (in its output parameter) a pointer to\na GdiplusStartupOutput structure. One of the members of the structure is a pointer to a notification\nunhook function that has the same signature as GdiplusNotificationUnhook. There are two ways you can\ncall the notification unhook function; you can use the pointer returned by GdiplusStartup or you\ncan call GdiplusNotificationUnhook. In fact, GdiplusNotificationUnhook simply verifies that you have\nsuppressed the background thread and then calls the notification unhook function that is returned by\nGdiplusStartup. When you call the notification unhook function, pass the token that you previously\nreceived from a corresponding call to the notification hook function. If you do not do this, there\nwill be resource leaks that won't be cleaned up until the process exits."

  DllCallGdipTestControl: "DllCall(\"gdiplus\\GdipTestControl\", \"GpTestControlEnum\", control, \"void *\", param, \"GpStatus\")\ncalled by wrappersUsed for internal testing of GDI+. Specifies changes in image-processing behavior.\nThe meaning of the param parameter varies depending on the value passed in the control parameter. If\nthe control parameter is set to TestControlForceBilinear, param points to a value of type BOOL. If\nthat value is TRUE and the current interpolation mode is anything other than InterpolationModeNearestNeighbor,\nthen the InterpolationModeBilinear algorithm is used. If the value pointed to by param is\nFALSE or if the current interpolation mode is InterpolationModeNearestNeighbor, then the behavior\nof GDI+ is unchanged. If the control parameter is set to TestControlNoICM, param points to a value of\ntype BOOL. If that value is TRUE, then ICM profiles are ignored when images are loaded into memory.\nIf the value pointed to by param is FALSE, then the behavior of GDI+ is unchanged. If the control\nparameter is set to TestControlGetBuildNumber, param is an output parameter that points to a 32-bit\ninteger variable. That variable receives the GDI+ build number. GdipTestControl is not thread-safe;\nit assumes that there is only one thread using GDI+. If you call GdipTestControl in a multithreaded\nenvironment, the results are unpredictable. The GpTestControlEnum enumeration has three elements: TestControlForceBilinear\n= 0, TestControlNoICM = 1, and TestControlGetBuildNumber = 2."

The type of information\nreturned depends on the dwFlags parameter and is based on the currently selected font in the specified\ndisplay context. The function copies the information to the specified GCP_RESULTS structure or to\none or more arrays specified by the structure.\nAlthough this function was once adequate for working\nwith character strings, a need to work with an increasing number of languages and scripts has rendered\nit obsolete. It has been superseded by the functionality of the Uniscribe module. For more information,\nsee Uniscribe.\nIt is recommended that an application use the GetFontLanguageInfo function to\ndetermine whether the GCP_DIACRITIC, GCP_DBCS, GCP_USEKERNING, GCP_LIGATE, GCP_REORDER, GCP_GLYPHSHAPE,\nand GCP_KASHIDA values are valid for the currently selected font. If not valid, GetCharacterPlacement\nignores the value.\nThe GCP_NODIACRITICS value is no longer defined and should not be used."

  DllCallIdnToAscii: "DllCall(\"Normaliz\\IdnToAscii\", \"_In_ DWORD\", dwFlags,\"_In_ LPCWSTR\", lpUnicodeCharStr,\"_In_ int\", cchUnicodeChar,\"_Out_opt_ LPWSTR\", lpASCIICharStr,\"_In_ int\", cchASCIIChar, \"int\")\nConverts an internationalized domain name (IDN) or another internationalized label to a Unicode (wide\ncharacter) representation of the ASCII string that represents the name in the Punycode transfer encoding\nsyntax. \nCaution   This function implements the RFC 3490: Internationalizing Domain Names in\nApplications (IDNA) standard algorithm for converting an IDN to Punycode. The standard introduces some\nsecurity issues. One issue is that glyphs representing certain characters from different scripts\nmight appear similar or even identical. For example, in many fonts, Cyrillic lowercase A ("?") is indistinguishable\nfrom Latin lowercase A ("a"). There is no way to tell visually that "example.com" and\n"ex?mple.com" are two different domain names, one with a Latin lowercase A in the name, the other\nwith a Cyrillic lowercase A. For more information about IDN-related security concerns, see Handling\nInternationalized Domain Names (IDNs)."

The token generated should be considered opaque by all callers.\nTypically, the InitializeSecurityContext (General) function is called in a loop until a sufficient\nsecurity context is established.\nFor information about using this function with a specific security\nsupport provider (SSP), see the following topics.\nTopicDescription\nInitializeSecurityContext (CredSSP)\nInitiates the client side, outbound security context from a credential handle by using the\nCredential Security Support Provider (CredSSP).\nInitializeSecurityContext (Digest) Initiates the client\nside, outbound security context from a credential handle by using the Digest security package.\nInitializeSecurityContext\n(Kerberos) Initiates the client side, outbound security context from a credential\nhandle by using the Kerberos security package.\nInitializeSecurityContext (Negotiate) Initiates\nthe client side, outbound security context from a credential handle by using the Negotiate security\npackage.\nInitializeSecurityContext (NTLM) Initiates the client side, outbound security context from\na credential handle by using the NTLM security package.\nInitializeSecurityContext (Schannel) Initiates\nthe client side, outbound security context from a credential handle by using the Schannel security\npackage."

  DllCallMultiByteToWideChar: "DllCall(\"Kernel32\\MultiByteToWideChar\", \"_In_ UINT\", CodePage,\"_In_ DWORD\", dwFlags,\"_In_ LPCSTR\", lpMultiByteStr,\"_In_ int\", cbMultiByte,\"_Out_opt_ LPWSTR\", lpWideCharStr,\"_In_ int\", cchWideChar, \"int\")\nMaps a character string to a UTF-16 (wide character) string. The character string is not necessarily\nfrom a multibyte character set.\nCaution  Using the MultiByteToWideChar function incorrectly can compromise\nthe security of your application. Calling this function can easily cause a buffer overrun because\nthe size of the input buffer indicated by lpMultiByteStr equals the number of bytes in the string,\nwhile the size of the output buffer indicated by lpWideCharStr equals the number of characters.\nTo avoid a buffer overrun, your application must specify a buffer size appropriate for the data type\nthe buffer receives. For more information, see Security Considerations: International Features.\nNote\n The ANSI code pages can be different on different computers, or can be changed for a single computer,\nleading to data corruption. For the most consistent results, applications should use Unicode,\nsuch as UTF-8 or UTF-16, instead of a specific code page, unless legacy standards or data formats prevent\nthe use of Unicode. If using Unicode is not possible, applications should tag the data stream\nwith the appropriate encoding name when protocols allow it. HTML and XML files allow tagging, but text\nfiles do not."

  DllCallTcAddFilter: "DllCall(\"Traffic\\TcAddFilter\", \"_In_ HANDLE\", FlowHandle,\"_In_ PTC_GEN_FILTER\", pGenericFilter,\"_Out_ PHANDLE\", pFilterHandle, \"ULONG\")\nThe\nTcAddFilter function associates a new filter with an existing flow that allows packets matching\nthe filter to be directed to the associated flow.\nFilters include a pattern and a mask. The pattern\nspecifies particular parameter values, while the mask specifies which parameters and parameter subfields\napply to a given filter. When a pattern/mask combination is applied to a set of packets, matching\npackets are directed to the flow to which the corresponding filter is associated.\nTraffic control\nreturns a handle to the newly added filter, in the pFilterHandle parameter, by which clients can refer\nto the added filter. Pending flows, such as those processing a TcAddFlow or TcModifyFlow request\nfor which a callback routine has not been completed, cannot have filters associated to them; only flows\nthat have been completed and are stable can apply associated filters.\nThe relationship between\nfilters and flows is many to one. Multiple filters can be applied to a single flow; however, a filter\ncan only apply to one flow. For example, flow A can have filters X, Y and Z applied to it, but as\nlong as flow A is active, filters X, Y and Z cannot apply to any other flows."
  DllCallTcAddFlow: "DllCall(\"Traffic\\TcAddFlow\", \"_In_ HANDLE\", IfcHandle,\"_In_ HANDLE\", ClFlowCtx,\"_In_ ULONG\", Flags,\"_In_ PTC_GEN_FLOW\", pGenericFlow,\"_Out_ PHANDLE\", pFlowHandle, \"ULONG\")\nThe TcAddFlow function adds a new flow on the specified interface. Note that the successful addition\nof a flow does not necessarily indicate a change in the way traffic is handled; traffic handling changes\nare effected by attaching a filter to the added flow, using the TcAddFilter function.\nTraffic\ncontrol clients that have registered an AddFlowComplete handler (a mechanism for allowing traffic control\nto call the ClAddFlowComplete callback function in order to alert clients of completed flow additions)\ncan expect a return value of ERROR_SIGNAL_PENDING. For more information, see Traffic Control\nObjects."

  DllCallTcEnumerateFlows: "DllCall(\"Traffic\\TcEnumerateFlows\", \"_In_ HANDLE\", IfcHandle,\"_Inout_ PHANDLE\", pEnumToken,\"_Inout_ PULONG\", pFlowCount,\"_Inout_ PULONG\", pBufSize,\"_Out_ PENUMERATION_BUFFER\", Buffer, \"ULONG\")\nThe\nTcEnumerateFlows function enumerates installed flows and their associated filters on an interface.\nThe process of returning flow enumeration often consists of multiple calls to the TcEnumerateFlows\nfunction. The process of receiving flow information from TcEnumerateFlows can be compared to reading\nthrough a book in multiple sittings, where a certain number of pages are read at one time, a bookmark\nis placed where reading stops, reading is resumed at the bookmark, and continues until the book\nis finished.\nThe TcEnumerateFlows function fills the Buffer parameter with as many flow enumerations\nas the buffer can hold, then returns a handle in the pEnumToken parameter that internally bookmarks\nwhere the enumeration stopped. Subsequent calls to TcEnumerateFlows must then pass the returned pEnumToken\nvalue to instruct traffic control where to resume flow enumeration information. When all flows\nhave been enumerated, pEnumToken will be NULL."

The new character string is not necessarily\nfrom a multibyte character set. \nCaution  Using the WideCharToMultiByte function incorrectly\ncan compromise the security of your application. Calling this function can easily cause a buffer overrun\nbecause the size of the input buffer indicated by lpWideCharStr equals the number of characters\nin the Unicode string, while the size of the output buffer indicated by lpMultiByteStr equals the\nnumber of bytes. To avoid a buffer overrun, your application must specify a buffer size appropriate\nfor the data type the buffer receives. \nData converted from UTF-16 to non-Unicode encodings is subject\nto data loss, because a code page might not be able to represent every character used in the specific\nUnicode data. For more information, see Security Considerations: International Features.\nNote\n  The ANSI code pages can be different on different computers, or can be changed for a single computer,\nleading to data corruption. For the most consistent results, applications should use Unicode, such\nas UTF-8 or UTF-16, instead of a specific code page, unless legacy standards or data formats prevent\nthe use of Unicode. If using Unicode is not possible, applications should tag the data stream with\nthe appropriate encoding name when protocols allow it. HTML and XML files allow tagging, but text\nfiles do not."
